>>50085440
When this was originally posted there was a link to an argument that the original meaning, and the pop-sci interpretation of it, are based on poor translations. Firstly, the early translations assume a rigidity in use of language that is modern, while literate Sumerians would play more fast and loose with the rules. If you've ever read Medieval works, you're familiar with this. People just wrote the way they though a word sounded, and you can often find 4 different spellings of the same word in a single work. The second is that the translations are also interpretations, and that the Sumerian expression for not seeing anything includes their word for "eyes". Hence, a better translation would be "A friendly local dog walks into the tavern. His eyes don't see a thing. He should open them".

It's not an abstract joke. It's a pun.

I think the stories about the unsafety of water are partly exaggerated due to that unfortunate recent period of historical interpretation where any old bullshit that painted history in a poor light was believed. People had wells and boiling vessels. More to the point, the Greeks and Romans watered their wine down, and considered drinking wine pure to be a barbarian thing to do. Especially the Romans, because they ended up exporting wine to Gaul, causing local alcoholism and gaining themselves a nice, captive market in the process. Literally, because they took payment in slaves. Point being, if Greeks and Romans drank wine because water was unsafe, they wouldn't have watered it down. But kraters (large wine-mixing vessels) are one of the most common finds from ancient Greece you'll see.

I'd go for the explanation of it happening from a settled life. Canines that lived as hunter gatherers or nomads until (historically) recently or still do look like wolves, those that have lived settled and agricultural lives for a very long time eventually became dog-like. Different breeds arose from different preferences being selected for, but it is effectively a genetic artifact that came from the change in lifestyle

There is a bit of a parallel to the real world here. There was an experiment which was started in the Soviet Union in the 1970s where a bunch of biologists bought silver foxes (a color morph of the red fox) from a fur farm, split them into a control group which would procreate as they wanted and a testing group which was selected for flight distance (the distance they ran away from humans). Despite being selected by only this criteria and nothing else, coat colorations never seen before and in some cases traits such as floppy ears and curly tails, as well behavioral patterns remarkably similar to dogs emerged without intention of creating these.
